JOHANNESBURG &#8211; South Africa&#8217;s rand firmed slightly on Wednesday as a major policy conference of the ruling ANC drew to a close and as the greenback slipped on concerns about rising tensions between the United States and North Korea.The rand was trading at 13.1475 versus the dollar at 0643 GMT, up 0.45% from its New York close on 13.2100.North Korea said on Wednesday it had conducted a test of a new intercontinental ballistic missile that can carry a large and heavy nuclear warhead.The ANC policy conference winds up, with analysts saying that radical plans within the ruling party for a complete overhaul of the economy appear not to have gained traction.&#8220;Our expectations remain that none of the most radical policies will be approved. This could be taken as a positive for the rand,&#8221; RMB Global Markets analyst John Cairns in a note.Stocks were set to open down 0.2%.Government bonds were firm, with the yield for the benchmark instrument due in 2026 down 3 basis points at 8.74%.